## Objective
Modify glamour's markdown rendering pipeline to apply syntax highlighting when processing fenced code blocks, seamlessly integrating with the existing pulldown-cmark based renderer.

## Detailed Requirements

### 1. Renderer Modification
Current code block handling (simplified):
```rust
// Current: plain text rendering
Event::Start(Tag::CodeBlock(kind)) => {
    // Push block start style
}
Event::Text(text) if in_code_block => {
    output.push_str(&code_style.render(&text));
}
Event::End(Tag::CodeBlock(_)) => {
    // Push block end style
}
```

New highlighted rendering:
```rust
#[cfg(feature = "syntax-highlighting")]
use crate::syntax::{LanguageDetector, SyntaxTheme, highlight_line};

pub struct Renderer {
    // ... existing fields
    #[cfg(feature = "syntax-highlighting")]
    lang_detector: LanguageDetector,
    #[cfg(feature = "syntax-highlighting")]
    syntax_theme: SyntaxTheme,
    current_code_lang: Option<String>,
}

impl Renderer {
    fn handle_event(&mut self, event: Event) {
        match event {
            Event::Start(Tag::CodeBlock(kind)) => {
                self.current_code_lang = match kind {
                    CodeBlockKind::Fenced(lang) => Some(lang.to_string()),
                    CodeBlockKind::Indented => None,
                };
                self.push_code_block_start();
            }

            Event::Text(text) if self.in_code_block() => {
                self.render_code_text(&text);
            }

            Event::End(Tag::CodeBlock(_)) => {
                self.current_code_lang = None;
                self.push_code_block_end();
            }

            // ... other events
        }
    }

    #[cfg(feature = "syntax-highlighting")]
    fn render_code_text(&mut self, text: &str) {
        if let Some(ref lang) = self.current_code_lang {
            let highlighted = self.highlight_code(text, lang);
            self.output.push_str(&highlighted);
        } else {
            // No language specified, render as plain
            self.output.push_str(&self.code_style.render(text));
        }
    }

    #[cfg(not(feature = "syntax-highlighting"))]
    fn render_code_text(&mut self, text: &str) {
        self.output.push_str(&self.code_style.render(text));
    }

    #[cfg(feature = "syntax-highlighting")]
    fn highlight_code(&self, code: &str, lang: &str) -> String {
        let syntax = self.lang_detector.detect(lang);
        let mut highlighter = HighlightLines::new(syntax, &self.syntax_theme.inner);
        let mut output = String::new();

        for line in LinesWithEndings::from(code) {
            let ranges = highlighter.highlight_line(line, &self.lang_detector.syntax_set)
                .unwrap_or_default();
            for (style, text) in ranges {
                let lg_style = syntect_to_lipgloss(style);
                output.push_str(&lg_style.render(text));
            }
        }

        output
    }
}
```

### 2. State Machine Updates
```
NORMAL -> CODE_BLOCK (on Start(CodeBlock))
    Store language identifier
    Initialize highlighter for language

CODE_BLOCK -> CODE_BLOCK (on Text)
    Highlight text with stored language
    Preserve line structure

CODE_BLOCK -> NORMAL (on End(CodeBlock))
    Clear language
    Finalize code block styling
```

### 3. Preserve Existing Styling
Code blocks should still have:
- Background color (from StyleConfig)
- Padding/margins
- Border (if configured)

The syntax highlighting applies WITHIN the code block style:
```rust
fn render_code_block(&mut self, highlighted_content: &str) {
    let block_style = self.config.code_block_style();
    // highlighted_content already has per-token colors
    // block_style adds the container styling
    self.output.push_str(&block_style.render(highlighted_content));
}
```

### 4. Edge Cases
- Empty code blocks: render empty styled block
- Very long lines: no special handling (terminal wraps)
- Binary/non-UTF8: fall back to plain text
- Nested code fences: handle correctly per CommonMark spec

## Acceptance Criteria
1. [ ] Code blocks with language hints are highlighted
2. [ ] Code blocks without language render as plain text
3. [ ] Existing code block styling (bg, padding) preserved
4. [ ] Line numbers preserved if configured
5. [ ] No performance regression >10% for docs without code
6. [ ] Feature flag correctly gates all highlighting code

## Implementation Notes
- Use LinesWithEndings to preserve line breaks correctly
- Consider streaming rendering for very large code blocks
- Test with nested/escaped code fences

